<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-416-122  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 416 122.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  April 11 1990 n130 p25(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business andamp; Computer Publications(England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Virus epidemic 'on its way.' (FoundationWare releases studyindicating that viruses may affect up to 8 million microcomputersworldwide by 1992)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   FoundationWare (reports).andO;Topic:     MicrocomputersData SecurityComputer VirusesReportsComputer CrimesInternationalForecasting.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Virus epidemic 'on its way' By 1995, computer viruses will reach 'epidemicproportions' if corporates do not initiate management strategies for theirPCs, according to a study carried out by US software house FoundationWare.andM;The research claims that by 1992 computer viruses will, directly orindirectly, affect up to 8 million PCs globally.andP;  &quot;This is a real threat tothe corporate community as a whole,&quot; commented FoundationWare's executivevice president, Michael Reimer.andP;  &quot;The potential costs to companies in dataloss, system downtime and data recovery efforts could well exceed 5 to 10billion dollars over the next five years.&quot;andM;Dr Peter Tippett, author of the report and president of FoundationWare,believes that the extensive computer virus hype has been damaging.andP;  &quot;It hasturned many people off, diverting the public, legislators and corporatemanagement from understanding how serious the problem truly is,&quot; he said.andM;The report concludes that if this situation is to be diverted, companies mustpull together a comprehensive system management strategy to protect their PCinstallations from malicious software replication.andO;</TEXT></DOC>